`crates/ctx-verify/tests/` is the black-box contract for `ctx-verify`'s check-running and reporting pipeline: it pins the parsing rules, orchestration status logic, and both CLI output formats (terse text and `--json`) against a fully faked subprocess layer, so no test here ever shells out.

Both files share the same `FakeRunner` pattern — canned `CommandOutcome`s keyed off a command's first argument, with an unmapped/`None` key simulating `CheckError::ToolMissing`. This keying is the single coupling point across the subtree: any change to how `checks.rs` invokes a tool (extra flag, reordered args, a new script path like `scripts/machete_check.sh`) requires updating the `by_first_arg` maps in *both* `checks.rs.ctx`'s tests and `render.rs.ctx`'s tests, since each builds its own map independently.

`checks.rs` covers the lower layer — pure parser correctness (`parse_compiler_json`, `parse_fail_lines`, `parse_fmt`) and orchestration semantics (`run_selected`, status precedence, diagnostic capping/truncation, minimal serde shape). `render.rs` covers the layer built on top — the CLI entry point (`cli::run`) and its two rendering modes, including the exact terse-text format (`"pass\n"`, `"FAIL: ..."` headers, `"… +N more"` truncation tail) and the JSON/text mutual exclusivity of the `status` field. Together they pin the full path from raw tool stdout to both machine- and human-facing output; a change to the diagnostic struct or status enum touches assertions in both files.